<h3>Logistics</h3>
<details>
  <summary>When do posts run on the site?</summary>
  <p>As of 2024, we post songs during the first <i>full</i> week of every month, starting Monday (e.g., February 5-9, 2014), with about three songs running per day.</p>
  <p>Historically, we ran three to four songs per day, every weekday. Our current posting schedule is an experiment -- you can help it go well!</p>
</details>
<details>
  <summary>What are the deadlines?</summary>
  <p>As a general rule, songs close around 9 PM Pacific US/12 AM Eastern US/5 AM England. We try to keep to this schedule as much as possible.</p>
  <p>Editors will try to announce when they're closing songs on Discord.</p>
</details>
<details>
  <summary>Help - a song is closed but I really really want to write about it!</summary>
  <p>Ping the day's editor ASAP by email or on Discord, and we'll try to accommodate, within reason.</p>
</details>
<details>
  <summary>Do blurbs autosave?</summary>
  <p>As of right now (January 2024), <strong>no</strong> - we advise keeping a copy of any longer in-progress blurbs. We hope to add this functionality soon.</p>
</details>
<details>
  <summary>Where can I get announcements about song closing times, scheduling, and special features -- and also hang out and talk music with you all?</summary>
  <p>Join our Discord! Ping any writer for an update. (Discord auto-expires invitation links after 7 days so we'll send you a new one.)
  <p>For major announcements, we also will email the writer mailing list, which you should have access to (ping Edward if not)</p>.
</details>
<h3>Songs and blurbing</h3>
<details>
  <summary>What songs should I write about?</summary>
  <p>We like to keep this open. Write about whichever songs you want to, as often or as rarely as works for you. If you haven’t written anything for weeks or months or years, we’ll welcome you back with open arms. We appreciate everyone offering whatever they have for free and don’t have any demands on frequency of writing.</p>
</details>
<details>
  <summary>What kinds of blurbs are you looking for?</summary>
  <p>We are deliberately open-ended about this: quick hits, deep musical dives, cutting contrarianism, poptimist enthusiasm, hot takes, and the occasional shitpost are all welcome, as long as they are at least somewhat related to the song.</p>
  <p>For more granular advice, see the <%= link_to "style guide", page_path(:style) %>.</p>
</details>
<details>
  <summary>How long should my blurb be?</summary>
  <p>Up to you! We've had everywhere from one-worders to longreads.</p>
</details>
<details>
  <summary>I really want to copy my blurb from Microsoft Word/Outlook/email into the text editor, but this causes formatting issues!</summary>
  <p>Solution 1: Copy blurb text into Notepad (Windows), TextEdit (Mac), or your browser address bar; this strips formatting automatically. Note that this also strips bold/italic/underline, and you'll have to re-add it.</p>
  <p>Solution 2: Use the alternate keyword shortcuts Ctrl+Shift+V (Windows) or Command+Option+Shift+V (Mac) while pasting. These also strip formatting.</p>
  <p>Solution 3: Compose directly in the blurber.</p>
</details>
<details>
  <summary>Can I use my blurbs elsewhere?</summary>
  <p>We’d like you to link back to us, but feel free to republish anything you write on the Jukebox on your blog or anywhere else. For Tumblr/Cohost posts, reblog whole Jukebox posts, or just reblog your blurb; either is great.</p>
</details>
<details>
  <summary>How do you choose what songs to cover?</summary>
  <p>A lot of factors: chart positions, streaming counts, coverage elsewhere, and general cultural impact; as well as genre diversity,previous Jukebox performance, writer enthusiasm, personal whims, and being interesting to write about.</p>
</details>
<details>
  <summary>I want us to write about X song - how can I make that happen?</summary>
  <p>Ask us! While we are currently running a limited set of songs, we're always happy to take suggestions, particularly of things off our radar. If you include some background info on the song/artist, we'll be more likely to be convinced.</p>
  <p>Or, wait until December; during our year-end Amnesty Week feature, writers choose one single from the past year for us to cover.</p>
</details>
